      '<p class="ql-align-justify"><strong style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);" class="ql-size-huge">FOMC Minutes: Did the Fed Pull the Trigger Too Hard?</strong></p><p class="ql-align-justify"><strong style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);" class="ql-size-large">Rate Cut Drama</strong></p><p class="ql-align-justify"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">So, the Fed just cut interest rates by 50 basis points, and you’d think that would be the end of the story. But no, the minutes from the September meeting reveal some drama behind the scenes. It turns out, that not everyone on the Fed’s Open Market Committee was on board with such an aggressive cut. Some members were like, “Maybe we should just go for 25 basis points, guys?” Their fear? On one side, inflation could creep back in. On the other, a bigger cut might scream, “The Fed is panicking!”</span></p><p class="ql-align-justify"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">But ultimately, 50bps won the day. And what’s happened since? Equities, especially Bitcoin, got a nice bump. Bitcoin surged up to $66.5k—its highest level since July—after the announcement.</span></p><p class="ql-align-justify"><strong style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);" class="ql-size-large">Why Was the Post-Cut Speech So Important?</strong></p><p class="ql-align-justify"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">Here’s the thing: the rate cut itself was just the beginning. Everyone was really waiting for the post-cut speech. Powell had to sell the “why” behind the cut—basically framing it as a ‘recalibration,’ not some sign of economic fear. He made sure to touch on all the key talking points: the labour market, inflation, and growth. His message? This cut will help keep the economy chugging along while we keep inflation in check. Apparently, the markets ate it up. The S&amp;P500 took it as good news and soared.</span></p><p class="ql-align-justify"><strong style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);" class="ql-size-large">S&amp;P500: Bullish Breakout or Just a Head Fake?</strong></p><p class="ql-align-justify"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">Take a look at the 5-minute chart of the S&amp;P500 and you’ll see just how wild these Fed presentations can get. The index spiked to $5783 after the minutes were released, then took a brief dip before breaking out to an all-time high (ATH) at $5807. It’s a bullish trend all the way, though the initial move might have caught some traders off guard. Classic trap.</span></p><p class="ql-align-center"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);"><img src="https://lh7-rt.googleuserraw_analysis.com/docsz/AD_4nXcknzySI0w1fKdXL_KeMCORH4excGjDuKaGtdZbEuoSc_wCaQZSnDOcZli8OzA72ozg7y6Odka2Z7xS4zauQna11vEI8Wx_U6nquLgyz00nbvBryu1Q88TWd-ZF_ItBiU842f6A9hTThYO-k7TKYWGS7hvI?key=QfE0Ad8i_MNlj3bU51pu0w" height="256"></span></p><p class="ql-align-center"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);" class="ql-size-small">S&amp;P500 5m Chart</span></p><p class="ql-align-justify"><strong style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);" class="ql-size-large">Bitcoin: The Struggle Continues</strong></p><p class="ql-align-justify"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">Now, contrast that with Bitcoin. While the S&amp;P500 was partying, Bitcoin took a 2.2% hit right after the Fed minutes came out. It dropped to around $60.3k, underscoring just how crucial that $60k support level is for liquidity. If Bitcoin breaks below $60k on a daily close, it could be in for a rough ride down to $58k, maybe even $55.6k. That’s the reversal zone from its recent high of $66.5k. In short, Bitcoin isn’t out of the woods yet.</span></p><p class="ql-align-center"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);"><img src="https://lh7-rt.googleuserraw_analysis.com/docsz/AD_4nXcjZ4I7naL0ITjIOuYqXMCFGWPMfjvF9ktZsxUseqaPFHZhRsCQapCsPfV8UgmHOFU0BZ_IzR9Bz3W_p3NR31ssK8SVgVh4lZwmpLl3mKYzTqFp68sK3J-_D8AWljnLexgje5qcP-3RTQqsdJKKL5Njp_w?key=QfE0Ad8i_MNlj3bU51pu0w" height="301"></span></p><p class="ql-align-center"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);" class="ql-size-small">BTC 5m Chart</span></p><p class="ql-align-justify"><strong style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);" class="ql-size-large">What is left for the market?</strong></p><ol><li class="ql-align-justify"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">The S&amp;P500 took a wild swing after the September FOMC minutes were released, initially dropping before shooting to new highs.</span></li><li class="ql-align-justify"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">Bitcoin didn’t fare as well. After hitting a $66.5k post-rate cut, it slid back to $60.3k, showing some clear signs of weakness compared to its earlier momentum.</span></li><li class="ql-align-justify"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">The minutes made it clear that any future rate cuts will hinge on the state of the labour market and inflation, putting both metrics firmly in the spotlight for upcoming decisions.</span></li><li class="ql-align-justify"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">Stay cautious—it’s a wild market out there, especially if you’re playing with leverage.</span></li></ol><p class="ql-align-justify"><em style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">&nbsp;AI Alpha is an educational tool and does not offer financial advice.</em></p>',
