      'Bitcoin vs. Bonds: Will Rising Yields Steal the Show?What’s the Deal with the 10Y Bond Yield?So, here’s the thing with Bitcoin lately—it’s been kind of sluggish, which is not what you’d expect when the S&P500 is hitting new highs. You’d think Bitcoin would be tagging along for the ride, but no. What happened? Well, part of it has to do with the 10-year bond auction that went down on Wednesday. The yield came in at 4.07%, which is the first time we’ve seen it break 4% since July. Big deal, right?The 10-year US Treasury bond is a bit like the thermometer for the economy. It measures how hot or cold things are going to be, and right now, it’s creeping back up. Bond yields like this one are auctioned off, and when the yield goes up while inflation is chilling around 2.5%, it usually means investors are seeing storm clouds ahead. Economic risks? Check. Less liquidity? Also, check. And that’s bad news for Bitcoin because, in an environment like this, people tend to get cosy with safe assets—like bonds—instead of rolling the dice with crypto.Why Are 10Y Bonds a Big Deal for Bitcoin?Here’s why the 10-year bond is the one to watch. When its yield is low, investors start looking for higher returns elsewhere, and that’s when risky assets like Bitcoin start looking pretty good. But, if the 10-year yield keeps rising, it’s like a magnet for all that investor cash. Suddenly, Bitcoin’s “alternative asset” appeal gets a bit of a hit. And since we’re seeing bond yields break out of their downtrend, Bitcoin might be in for a tougher time.The 10-year yield is now sitting above 4%, a level it last fell below in August when the Jobless Claims report spooked everyone. If the yield keeps climbing, the next resistance is between 4.3% and 4.5%. For the markets to stay in “Risk On” mode—where risky assets like Bitcoin benefit—we need those levels to hold. If not, investors might start heading for the exits.US-10Y & BTC 4H ChartWhy Is Bitcoin Falling Despite Stock Market Gains?It’s kind of weird, though. Bitcoin has been bearish all week, even as the S&P500 hit an all-time high near $5800. Historically, Bitcoin tends to get a boost when stocks do well, but it seems like bonds might be throwing a wrench in that correlation. Rising yields can siphon off liquidity, leaving less room for assets like Bitcoin to thrive. Safe haven assets like bonds are taking the spotlight, while crypto is left waiting for its turn.What is left for the market?The 10Y bond auction yield hit 4.07% with 2.5% inflation, signalling investors aren’t rushing to grab government debt.Bitcoin is looking weak while the stock market is out here setting fresh highs—it’s not following the usual script.If bond yields keep climbing, don’t be surprised if riskier assets like Bitcoin take a hit as investors seek safer returns.Stay cautious—it’s a wild market out there, especially if you’re playing with leverage. AI Alpha is an educational tool and does not offer financial advice.',
